168
00:06:01,361 --> 00:06:03,002
who were very involved in the scene creation.

169
00:06:04,163 --> 00:06:06,724
We had roughly two years at that time to finish our story.

170
00:06:07,225 --> 00:06:08,625
And yes, it was freaking daunting.

171
00:06:08,945 --> 00:06:10,466
I mean, so many of us were really concerned

172
00:06:10,486 --> 00:06:12,928
with the fact that we were jumping into a character

173
00:06:12,968 --> 00:06:16,249
that was arguably overly saturated in the market.

174
00:06:16,409 --> 00:06:17,590
Maybe people are bored with him.

175
00:06:17,870 --> 00:06:19,031
What were they going to like what we made?

176
00:06:19,471 --> 00:06:20,852
So I was pretty freaked out.

177
00:06:22,052 --> 00:06:25,034
So, just to give you a high-level view of our process when it comes to creating cinematics,

178
00:06:25,094 --> 00:06:26,055
we start with Previs.

179
00:06:26,535 --> 00:06:31,437
Most of our animators will jump into doing thumbnails or animatics on their own, but

180
00:06:31,458 --> 00:06:34,739
that's not something that we've actually incorporated into our workflow because in my experience

181
00:06:34,759 --> 00:06:38,821
and in the experience of our team, it's much more efficient for us to jump into 3D as fast

182
00:06:38,861 --> 00:06:39,382
as possible.

183
00:06:41,666 --> 00:06:44,868
Once we identify our previews, we get to a level of time lock,

184
00:06:45,288 --> 00:06:49,070
then we'll identify what we can animate with hand-keying,

185
00:06:49,110 --> 00:06:50,311
which is a lot of the Spider-Man work

186
00:06:50,351 --> 00:06:51,632
or a lot of the villains that are in the scene.

187
00:06:52,972 --> 00:06:55,854
Or we'll identify the scenes that we need to take to PCAP.

188
00:06:57,633 --> 00:06:59,475
After we get data back from performance capture,

189
00:06:59,635 --> 00:07:00,716
we'll lay the scene out again.

190
00:07:01,357 --> 00:07:03,720
Part of that is because we don't want to infect

191
00:07:03,780 --> 00:07:05,081
our animators with, or excuse me,

192
00:07:05,141 --> 00:07:06,943
our actors with our previews.

193
00:07:07,264 --> 00:07:09,126
In most cases, we don't even show them our previews.

194
00:07:09,166 --> 00:07:10,808
We give them good blocking instruction.

195
00:07:10,828 --> 00:07:11,989
We tell them where the cameras will be,

196
00:07:12,289 --> 00:07:14,412
but we want them to help bring about the performance.

197
00:07:14,452 --> 00:07:18,076
We want them to help us make a better character

198
00:07:18,136 --> 00:07:18,797
or a better scene.

199
00:07:19,882 --> 00:07:21,243
which requires us to layout again.

200
00:07:21,963 --> 00:07:24,646
After we get through a number of weeks of animating

201
00:07:24,706 --> 00:07:27,648
and working on layout and coming to a final edit,

202
00:07:28,148 --> 00:07:30,210
animation is finally ready to release that scene

203
00:07:30,350 --> 00:07:31,091
to the other departments

204
00:07:31,111 --> 00:07:32,392
that will help bring these things to final

205
00:07:32,412 --> 00:07:33,613
and actually make them so much better

206
00:07:33,633 --> 00:07:34,554
than we can create on our own.

207
00:07:35,254 --> 00:07:37,957
So we lock the edit, we release it to visual effects,

208
00:07:38,737 --> 00:07:40,599
lighting and audio and score

209
00:07:40,639 --> 00:07:42,220
and anyone else who has to contribute to the scene.

210
00:07:43,648 --> 00:07:45,814
And finally, concurrently now at that point,

211
00:07:45,834 --> 00:07:47,679
we're polishing the scenes, we're fixing bugs,

212
00:07:48,060 --> 00:07:49,685
and we're banging away on many other scenes.

213
00:07:51,245 --> 00:07:52,145
So, Previs.

214
00:07:52,965 --> 00:07:54,386
Generally speaking, at Insomniac,

215
00:07:54,526 --> 00:07:56,086
we assign one scene per animator,

216
00:07:56,106 --> 00:07:57,707
and we try and cast these scenes out

217
00:07:57,767 --> 00:07:59,487
to animators that have strengths and weaknesses.

218
00:07:59,507 --> 00:08:01,068
But we're not limited to that.

219
00:08:01,088 --> 00:08:02,068
We don't want to pigeonhole people,

220
00:08:02,108 --> 00:08:03,629
so we allow them to try different scenes.

221
00:08:04,329 --> 00:08:07,230
We iterate exhaustively on Previs, especially on i20.

222
00:08:07,310 --> 00:08:08,810
We would meet twice a week,

223
00:08:08,950 --> 00:08:10,891
where we would gather together the entire cinematic team

224
00:08:10,931 --> 00:08:12,611
