262
00:09:40,060 --> 00:09:42,202
We're not crossing the line of action unintentionally.

263
00:09:42,942 --> 00:09:44,043
Scene geography makes sense.

264
00:09:44,063 --> 00:09:44,924
You know where actors are.

265
00:09:45,224 --> 00:09:46,245
And then we take another pass.

266
00:09:46,265 --> 00:09:49,327
We jump back in and try and infuse subtext as best we can.

267
00:09:49,667 --> 00:09:51,609
And that could be altering compositions,

268
00:09:52,429 --> 00:09:53,970
moving the character to the center of the screen,

269
00:09:53,991 --> 00:09:55,311
or offsetting and having them look

270
00:09:55,332 --> 00:09:56,312
into the short side of the screen

271
00:09:56,352 --> 00:09:57,593
to let the audience feel awkward,

272
00:09:58,494 --> 00:10:01,416
or looking for frames within frames or other opportunities.

273
00:10:01,876 --> 00:10:04,198
And again, this is a massive art form in and of itself.

274
00:10:04,899 --> 00:10:06,600
I won't go too deep into it, but it's something

275
00:10:06,640 --> 00:10:08,320
that so many people on our team are really

276
00:10:08,360 --> 00:10:10,402
working hard to do in addition to being animators.

277
00:10:11,522 --> 00:10:15,124
So another thing, we have to shoot a lot of dialogue scenes

